-- ── Gogs ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Gogs is a lightweight, open-source, self-hosted Git service written in Go that lets teams run their own GitHub-like code hosting platform on minimal hardware.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (self-hosted)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2014, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Gogs Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Gogs review covering this open-source, self-hosted Git service: features, MIT licensing, hardware requirements, and how it compares to Gitea and GitLab.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Gogs is an open-source, self-hosted Git service written in the Go programming language, created in 2014 by developer Joe Chen (known online as unknwon). Its stated mission is to provide 'a simple, stable and extensible self-hosted Git service that can be set up in the most painless way,' and it was one of the pioneering projects to prove that a full-featured GitHub-style code hosting platform could ship as a single, dependency-free binary rather than a complex multi-service stack. Because Go compiles to static binaries for every major platform, Gogs runs identically on Linux, macOS, Windows, and ARM-based systems such as a Raspberry Pi, and its minimal footprint means a small cloud droplet costing around five dollars a month, or even a single-board computer, is enough to host a working instance for a small team; a baseline collaborative setup is comfortable with roughly two CPU cores and 512MB of RAM. The project is released under the permissive MIT License, so it can be freely deployed, modified, and redistributed for both personal and commercial use with no licensing fees, and there is no separate paid or cloud-hosted tier — the entire value proposition is a free binary that organizations run on their own infrastructure. Gogs is community-maintained on GitHub, where it has accumulated tens of thousands of stars (over 47,000), reflecting its long-running popularity among developers who want a lightweight self-hosted alternative to GitHub, GitLab, or Bitbucket. Architecturally, Gogs is a monolithic web application built primarily in Go (roughly two-thirds of the codebase) with a Go-templated frontend and a TypeScript- and JavaScript-based UI layer for interactive elements, and it supports multiple database backends including PostgreSQL, MySQL, MariaDB, and SQLite3, giving administrators flexibility to match the datastore to their scale, from a single SQLite file for a hobby project up to a dedicated PostgreSQL server for a larger organization. Core features mirror the essentials expected of a modern Git hosting platform: repository hosting over SSH, HTTP, and HTTPS; a personal and organizational dashboard with activity timelines; pull requests and code review workflows; a built-in wiki per repository; protected branch rules; repository migration and mirroring from other Git hosts; webhook integrations for services like Slack, Discord, and DingTalk; and authentication options including SMTP, LDAP, reverse proxy, and GitHub-based login for enterprise and self-hosted identity setups. The interface is localized into roughly 31 languages, making it broadly accessible outside English-speaking markets. Historically, Gogs holds a notable place in the self-hosted Git ecosystem as the project that Gitea forked from in 2016. That fork happened because a group of contributors wanted faster release cycles, broader community governance, and more openness to outside pull requests than Gogs' single-maintainer model allowed, since Gogs has effectively remained under the control of its original founder rather than adopting a foundation or multi-maintainer governance structure. In the years since, Gitea has substantially outpaced Gogs in feature velocity, contributor count, and ecosystem adoption, and has itself since spawned further forks such as Codeberg's Forgejo, making Gogs more of a foundational ancestor project than the most actively evolving option in its category today. Despite this, Gogs remains functional, maintained, and still widely deployed by users who value its minimalism, small binary size, and the stability of a project that has not chased every new feature trend. The target audience for Gogs is developers, small teams, and self-hosting enthusiasts who want full control over their source code without relying on a third-party SaaS provider, who are comfortable running and maintaining their own server, and who prioritize a lightweight footprint and simple setup over the broader feature set of GitLab (which includes built-in CI/CD, container registries, and security scanning) or the faster-moving development pace of Gitea. It's a natural fit for privacy-conscious organizations, students and hobbyists running Git on inexpensive hardware, and companies in regulated industries that require on-premises code hosting. Competitively, Gogs sits at the lightweight end of the self-hosted Git spectrum: it is simpler to install and run than GitLab Community Edition, has a smaller resource footprint than most alternatives, but offers fewer built-in DevOps features (no native CI/CD, for example) than either GitLab or Gitea, both of which have added substantially more functionality since Gogs' original release. For teams that just need dependable, self-hosted Git repository management with pull requests, wikis, and webhooks — without the operational overhead of a heavier platform — Gogs remains a viable, cost-free option, though most new self-hosted deployments today tend to gravitate toward Gitea or Forgejo given their faster pace of development.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '610f2fd5-da8a-4b36-8a7f-bf94d0307b17';

