-- ── Goldcast ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Goldcast is an AI-powered B2B event marketing platform for webinars, virtual events, and video content repurposing, acquired by Cvent in December 2025.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Custom / Quote-based (Enterprise SaaS)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (Content Lab); custom annual contracts for Events and Enterprise plans$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2020, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Approximately 200 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Cambridge, Massachusetts, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Goldcast Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Goldcast review covering this AI event marketing and webinar platform: features, pricing tiers, the Cvent acquisition, pros, cons, and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Goldcast is a B2B event marketing and content repurposing platform founded in 2020 by Kishore Kothandaraman, Palash Soni, and Aashish Srinivas, headquartered in the Cambridge/Boston, Massachusetts area. It positions itself as a modern alternative to legacy webinar and virtual-event tools such as ON24, Zoom Events, and Webex Events, targeting B2B marketing teams that run frequent webinars, virtual conferences, and hybrid events as part of their demand generation and pipeline strategy. Over its life as an independent company, Goldcast raised a total of roughly 42 million dollars in funding across three rounds from investors including WestBridge Capital, Underscore VC, and Wellfound. In a significant milestone for the company, Goldcast was acquired by Cvent, the large publicly traded event management software provider, in December 2025, folding Goldcast's AI-driven content and webinar capabilities into Cvent's broader event technology suite; this acquisition is an important piece of context for any buyer evaluating Goldcast today, since its roadmap and go-to-market will now be shaped as part of Cvent rather than as a standalone venture-backed startup. Goldcast's product spans three interconnected pillars. The first is Recording Studio, a browser-based HD recording environment that captures individual audio and video tracks per speaker, supports dynamic scene changes and branded overlays during live production, and is built so that recorded sessions can be instantly repurposed into other formats rather than sitting as a single unedited video file. The second pillar is Events, the live and on-demand webinar and virtual-event hosting layer, which includes automatic calendar holds for registrants, interactive elements like polls, Q and A, and on-screen overlays during live sessions, and seamless transition of live content into on-demand libraries after the event ends, with automatic repurposing pipelines kicking in once a session concludes. The third and most distinctive pillar is Content Lab, an AI-powered repurposing engine that takes recorded video or webinar content and automatically generates multi-modal outputs such as blog posts, short social clips, and other derivative content assets, using an AI system trained to match a company's specific brand voice, alongside AI-powered search across a company's video and event library so marketing teams can find and reuse specific moments from past content. This repurposing focus is Goldcast's core differentiator versus traditional webinar platforms, which primarily treat a webinar as a single live broadcast event rather than as a raw material source for an entire content marketing pipeline. Enterprise-oriented capabilities layered on top include team workspaces, single sign-on (SSO), custom reporting, granular permissions, and multi-language support, positioning the platform for marketing organizations that need governance controls across multiple teams and regions running events simultaneously. On pricing, Goldcast does not publish detailed self-serve tiers on its marketing site; potential customers are directed to request a demo or contact sales. Content Lab has a 'get started for free' entry point, giving prospective customers a way to try the AI repurposing features before committing to a paid contract. Beyond that free entry point, pricing is structured around annual contracts that scale with the number of events run, expected attendee volume, feature tier, and contract length, rather than simple flat per-seat SaaS pricing. Industry pricing analyses based on anonymized deal data generally describe three rough tiers: an Essentials tier typically running from about 12,000 to 30,000 dollars annually, a mid-tier Growth plan, and an Enterprise tier that can range from roughly 70,000 to over 150,000 dollars annually depending on event scale, attendee caps, and add-on modules; overall contract values across the customer base have been observed ranging from about 12,000 dollars up to well over 100,000 dollars per year. The platform also supports monthly payment options for customers who prefer not to commit to a full annual upfront payment. Goldcast's target audience is primarily B2B marketing teams at mid-market and enterprise software or services companies that run a heavy cadence of webinars and virtual events as core demand-generation channels, and who want each event to generate a large volume of downstream content (clips, blog posts, social assets) without a separate video editing or content team doing that work manually. Competitively, Goldcast differentiates from pure webinar tools like Zoom Events or Webex Events by treating content repurposing as a first-class product pillar rather than an afterthought, and differentiates from all-purpose event platforms like Hopin or vFairs by focusing tightly on the B2B marketing use case rather than large-scale conference logistics. Following its acquisition by Cvent, Goldcast's near-term positioning is likely to shift toward being the AI content and webinar layer within a larger, more comprehensive event management ecosystem that also includes Cvent's established in-person and hybrid event registration, venue sourcing, and attendee management tools.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'ebccc093-34ed-4258-b26b-8a95b2400c1e';

