-- ── GoModel ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$GoModel is an open-source, MIT-licensed AI gateway written in Go that gives applications one OpenAI- and Anthropic-compatible endpoint across 22+ model providers with caching and cost controls.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Open Source (self-hosted); custom enterprise options via Enterpilot$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (self-hosted)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(NULL, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$GoModel Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$GoModel review covering this open-source AI gateway: routing, caching, guardrails, usage tracking, licensing, and how it compares to LiteLLM.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$GoModel is an open-source AI gateway built by Enterpilot and written in the Go programming language, designed to give applications a single, stable, OpenAI- and Anthropic-compatible API endpoint that sits in front of more than 22 underlying AI model providers, including OpenAI, Anthropic, Google Gemini, Azure OpenAI, AWS Bedrock, Groq, xAI, Ollama, and vLLM, among others. Its core value proposition is one that has become increasingly important as engineering teams adopt multiple large language model providers simultaneously: instead of every application maintaining separate SDKs, authentication, and error handling for each provider, teams point their code at GoModel once, and GoModel handles the routing, failover, and provider-specific translation behind the scenes. It is explicitly positioned in the market as an open-source alternative to commercial or semi-commercial AI gateway products like LiteLLM, aimed at teams that want a lightweight, self-hosted, single-binary solution rather than a heavier managed service. The project is released under the permissive MIT License and ships as a single Go binary distributed via a compact roughly 16MB Docker image, requiring no proprietary dependencies to run, which keeps deployment simple whether a team is running it on a laptop for local development or on production infrastructure serving real traffic. Functionally, GoModel organizes its capabilities into three broad areas. The first is routing and provider management: model aliases let teams define a stable internal model name (for example, an alias like 'production-chat-model') that can be repointed to a different underlying provider or model version without changing any application code, which is valuable for hedging against provider price changes, outages, or deprecations. This is paired with automatic failover, circuit breaker protection, retry logic, and load balancing across multiple API keys and providers, so that if one provider experiences an outage or rate limit, requests can be automatically rerouted to a backup without manual intervention. The second area is cost and performance control, which includes exact-match response caching that returns identical repeated requests faster and without incurring a new API charge, as well as semantic caching backed by vector databases such as Qdrant, pgvector, Pinecone, or Weaviate, allowing GoModel to recognize and cache responses to semantically similar (not just identical) prompts. On top of caching, GoModel supports per-team and per-tenant budget enforcement with real-time spend tracking, and detailed usage analytics that break down token consumption and cost on a per-request basis, which is particularly relevant for multi-tenant SaaS platforms that need to bill or cap usage per customer. The third area is safety and observability: GoModel supports scoped workflows that let administrators apply different policies depending on the provider, model, or user path being invoked, alongside guardrails capable of system prompt injection and message rewriting to enforce organizational policy on outbound and inbound content, comprehensive audit logging with full request tracing for compliance and debugging, and an embedded admin dashboard paired with Prometheus metrics for operational monitoring. Architecturally, a request flows through a defined pipeline of authentication, workflow resolution, guardrails, cache lookup, rate limiting, and finally provider routing, and the gateway supports native streaming without buffering, meaning token-by-token streamed responses from an underlying LLM provider pass through GoModel without added latency from full-response buffering. For storage, GoModel is designed to scale from a lightweight embedded SQLite database for small or local deployments up through PostgreSQL or MongoDB for larger production workloads, letting a single codebase serve both a solo developer's local project and a company-wide production deployment. Because GoModel is fully open source with no license fee, its direct cost to run is limited to whatever infrastructure it is deployed on; there is no tiered SaaS pricing published for the open-source gateway itself. However, GoModel is built by Enterpilot, a company whose primary commercial product is a hosted AI access and traffic management platform for enterprises that need centralized control, observability, guardrails, anonymization, and cost governance across all AI usage inside an organization, offered through SaaS, on-premises, or bring-your-own-cloud (BYOC) deployment models with custom, sales-negotiated pricing. In effect, GoModel functions as an accessible, self-hostable, developer-first entry point into the same problem space that Enterpilot's commercial platform addresses at enterprise scale, similar to how some open-source projects serve as a funnel toward a related paid enterprise product. The target audience for GoModel spans individual developers and platform teams who want to standardize how their applications talk to multiple LLM providers without vendor lock-in, multi-tenant SaaS builders who need per-customer budget enforcement and usage tracking baked into their AI infrastructure layer, cost-conscious teams who want to reduce redundant API spend through caching, and compliance-focused organizations that require detailed audit trails of every AI request made across their systems. Competitively, GoModel's closest comparison point is LiteLLM, another popular AI gateway/proxy project, and GoModel differentiates itself primarily through its Go-based single-binary architecture (versus Python-based alternatives), its compact footprint, and its explicit focus on multi-tenant budget and usage governance as a first-class feature rather than an add-on.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '15d61a4f-9e28-4299-9ecb-c1c0998fc971';

