-- ── Gong ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Gong is an AI-powered revenue intelligence platform that records, transcribes, and analyzes sales calls, emails, and meetings to surface deal risk and coach reps.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription (custom/enterprise quote-based)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Custom pricing (~$1,600/user/year plus an annual platform fee)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2015, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$1,000-2,500 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Francisco, California, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Gong Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Gong review covering this revenue intelligence platform: AI call analysis, deal intelligence, pricing breakdown, pros, cons, and top alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Gong is a revenue intelligence platform founded in 2015 by CEO Amit Bendov and CPO Eilon Reshef, headquartered in San Francisco, California, that uses artificial intelligence to record, transcribe, and analyze sales conversations across calls, video meetings, and emails in order to give revenue teams visibility into what is actually happening in their pipeline. The company grew rapidly on the strength of enterprise sales team adoption and raised a total of approximately 583 million dollars in venture funding across seven rounds, including a 250 million dollar Series E in 2021 led by Franklin Templeton Investments at a 7.25 billion dollar valuation, with other notable investors including Coatue, Sequoia Capital, Thrive Capital, and Salesforce Ventures. More recently, a secondary share sale conducted through the Nasdaq Private Market in November 2025 valued the company at approximately 4.5 billion dollars, below its 2021 peak, reflecting the broader repricing of late-stage software valuations since the 2021 funding peak. Gong reports around 500 million dollars in annual recurring revenue as of 2026, and employee counts vary by source and date, with figures ranging from roughly 1,300 to 2,500 people, reflecting Gong's position as a large, well-established scale-up rather than an early-stage startup. Gong's core product is organized around what the company calls Deal Intelligence, People Intelligence, and Market Intelligence. Deal Intelligence uses AI to analyze recorded sales conversations and CRM data to flag at-risk deals, surface competitor mentions, track buyer sentiment and engagement signals, and forecast pipeline outcomes with more accuracy than manager intuition or manually updated CRM fields alone. People Intelligence focuses on rep performance and coaching: it identifies talk patterns, objection handling, and messaging that correlates with won versus lost deals, and gives sales managers a scalable way to coach reps by reviewing actual call recordings and AI-generated highlights rather than relying on spot-checked ride-alongs. Market Intelligence aggregates conversation data in aggregate across the customer base to surface market trends, competitive positioning shifts, and product feedback patterns that emerge organically from thousands of real customer conversations. Underlying all three pillars is Gong's conversation intelligence engine, which transcribes and analyzes recorded interactions using natural language processing and, increasingly, generative AI to summarize calls, draft follow-up emails, and answer natural-language questions about deal status across the whole revenue organization. Gong integrates tightly with CRM systems (especially Salesforce), calendar and conferencing tools like Zoom and Microsoft Teams, and email platforms, positioning itself as a layer that sits on top of the existing sales tech stack rather than replacing the CRM itself. On pricing, Gong does not publish self-serve rates; the product is sold entirely through a direct enterprise sales process with pricing individually negotiated per customer. The base Gong Foundations product is commonly reported to price around 1,600 dollars per user per year at list price, though negotiated deals frequently land in the 1,000 to 1,349 dollar per user per year range depending on deal size and negotiating leverage. On top of per-user licensing, nearly all customers also pay a mandatory annual platform fee ranging from roughly 5,000 to 50,000 dollars regardless of team size, plus a one-time onboarding fee typically starting around 7,500 dollars for most implementations. Gong also sells add-on modules priced separately, including Gong Forecast (roughly 700 dollars per user per year) for AI-assisted revenue forecasting and Gong Engage (roughly 800 dollars per user per year) for sales engagement and outreach workflows. Industry pricing analysts note that Gong's effective per-user cost rose between 25 and 56 percent from 2023 to 2026 following a March 2025 pricing restructuring, and that when platform fees, onboarding costs, bundled add-ons, and inactive seats are factored in, the total effective cost of a Gong deployment can run two to three times higher than the advertised per-seat rate alone, making budgeting and negotiation a genuinely important part of evaluating the platform. Gong holds strong customer satisfaction scores, with a 4.7 out of 5 star rating on G2 across more than 6,500 reviews, reflecting high perceived value despite the premium pricing, particularly among mid-market and enterprise B2B sales organizations. The target audience for Gong is primarily mid-market and enterprise revenue organizations — sales, customer success, and revenue operations teams — at companies with complex, multi-stakeholder B2B sales cycles where visibility into individual deals and rep behavior materially affects win rates and forecast accuracy. Competitively, Gong is generally considered the category leader and pricing benchmark in the conversation and revenue intelligence space, competing most directly with Chorus (owned by ZoomInfo), Clari, and a wave of newer, often lower-priced AI-native entrants; Gong differentiates through the depth and maturity of its AI analysis, its large training dataset from years of aggregated call data across its customer base, and its expanding platform ambitions beyond pure call recording into forecasting and engagement, though this expansion has also made it one of the more expensive options in its category.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'e0177a50-1ba8-4919-b2dc-e93170edc86f';

